title: Measurement of isotopic cross sections of spallation residues in 800 A*MeV Au-197+P collisions.

x4freetext: Measurement of isotopic cross sections of spallation
residues in 800 A*MeV Au-197+P collisions.

x4freetext: All data were taken from the
preprint
Reference is corrected
Last checking has been done.
A 1 cm thick liquid-hydrogen target was inserted at the
bottom of a helium cryostat between thin titanium foils
of 36 mg/cm**2 thickness. A thin niobium foil of
60 mg/cm**2 was placed behind the target to increase
the rate of bare ions. The number of hydrogen atoms per
unit area in the beam line was 60 time larger than the
number of titanium and niobium atoms.  As the
geometrica cross section of gold reaction is about 3
times larger in titanium and niobium than in hydrogen,
the total reaction rate was in average 20 times larger
in the hydrogen target than in the surrounding
materials. The thickness of hydrogen at the centre of
the target was thus deduced and determined to be
.A MONTE-CARLO code and a semi-empirical
parameterization.
The mean kinetic energies of the fragments are deduced
from the experimental data.
Mass and charge distribution.
. Position-sensitive plastic scintillators and
the multi-wire detectors.

x4freetext: The total uncertainty of the cross section
results from the combined uncertainty on each
correction factor. The total uncertainty of the cross
sections is lower than 15% from mercury down to
dysprosium isotopes. For lighter products, due to the
increasing contribution of multiple reaction in the
target and secondary reactions in the target windows,
uncertainty amounts to 20% from terbium to europium,
and is of the order of 30% for the lightest fragments
between samarium and neodymium. The uncertainty of the
cross sections resulting from the statistics of the
measurement and from the precision in the
identification is limited to about the half of the
total combined uncertainty of the different correction
factors.
In the preprint
-By authors. Different corrections must be applied-
-the losses due to the transmission through the
spectrometer,
-the losses due to secondary reactions in the
different layers of matter in the beam line,
-the contribution to the reaction rate from multiple
reactions inside the hydrogen target,
-the losses due to atomic charge changing in the
different layers of matter in the beam line,
-dead time of the data acquisition,
-the efficiency of the detectors.
- By compiler - all cross sections are independent ones
